WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.470 --> 00:00:10.300
MALE SPEAKER: Good morning
and welcome to Talks at Google

00:00:10.300 --> 00:00:12.110
in Cambridge, Mass.

00:00:12.110 --> 00:00:14.360
Today it's my great
pleasure to introduce

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:19.140
one of the most interesting
people I know, Bill Powers.

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:21.840
Bill has worked for two
decades in development aid

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:25.910
and conservation in Latin
America, Africa and North

00:00:25.910 --> 00:00:27.380
America.

00:00:27.380 --> 00:00:32.420
From 2002 to 2004 he managed
the community components

00:00:32.420 --> 00:00:35.340
of a project in
the Bolivian Amazon

00:00:35.340 --> 00:00:39.540
that won a 2003 prize for
environmental innovation

00:00:39.540 --> 00:00:43.040
from the Kennedy School
of Government at Harvard.

00:00:43.040 --> 00:00:45.050
He's worked at the
World Bank and holds

00:00:45.050 --> 00:00:49.340
international relations degrees
from Brown and Georgetown.

00:00:49.340 --> 00:00:52.930
He's a Senior Fellow at
the World Policy Institute

00:00:52.930 --> 00:00:57.660
and an adjunct faculty member
at New York University.

00:00:57.660 --> 00:01:00.810
"New Slow City" is his
fourth book for adults.

00:01:00.810 --> 00:01:03.860
They're all excellent, and
you can read more about them

00:01:03.860 --> 00:01:10.830
on his website
www.williampowersbook.com.

00:01:10.830 --> 00:01:15.340
So, burned out after years of
doing everything I just listed,

00:01:15.340 --> 00:01:19.150
Bill spent a season in
a 12 foot by 12 cabin

00:01:19.150 --> 00:01:21.990
off the grid in North Carolina.

00:01:21.990 --> 00:01:24.320
He then attempted to
do something similar

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:26.030
in New York City.

00:01:26.030 --> 00:01:29.360
I suspect we're about to get
an entirely new perspective

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:33.510
on work life balance, as
well as the benefit of Bill's

00:01:33.510 --> 00:01:37.770
extensive experience in
international affairs.

00:01:37.770 --> 00:01:41.072
Please join me in
welcoming, Bill Powers.

00:01:41.072 --> 00:01:43.772
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:43.772 --> 00:01:44.730
BILL POWERS: Thank you.

00:01:44.730 --> 00:01:48.030
Thanks very much for
coming on a Monday morning

00:01:48.030 --> 00:01:50.450
to this gathering.

00:01:50.450 --> 00:01:53.630
It's just a great pleasure
to be here at Google.

00:01:53.630 --> 00:01:56.640
I use your products and I
think they're wonderful.

00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:59.410
And, because you're such
an intelligent audience,

00:01:59.410 --> 00:02:02.530
I'm going to try to pack
a lot in to this hour we

00:02:02.530 --> 00:02:03.600
have together.

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:08.270
And I'm going to really give
some perspectives on what

00:02:08.270 --> 00:02:11.039
is the philosophical
underpinning for these new slow

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:15.090
movements and movements towards
minimalism and simplicity

00:02:15.090 --> 00:02:19.110
and work life balance,
and why it's happening now

00:02:19.110 --> 00:02:21.830
with the environmental crisis
and the triple threat that's

00:02:21.830 --> 00:02:22.600
happening.

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:24.820
And I'm also going to share
some personal experiences

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:27.280
from my own life-- this journey
that Jonathan was talking

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:30.870
about from New York City,
all around the world,

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:33.150
to a tiny 12 by 12
cabin in North Carolina,

00:02:33.150 --> 00:02:36.270
and so on-- as a way of
provoking questions and maybe

00:02:36.270 --> 00:02:38.520
inspiring you to think
about some new things

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:41.070
that you can do in your
work and your life.

00:02:41.070 --> 00:02:43.190
You take from it what you will.

00:02:43.190 --> 00:02:48.050
So with that said,
we're in this moment

00:02:48.050 --> 00:02:50.640
of what you might call
the Great Turning,

00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:57.950
where there are related
movements around slow issues.

00:02:57.950 --> 00:03:00.694
Like fast food is being
replaced by slow food.

00:03:00.694 --> 00:03:02.110
You know about
this slow movement.

00:03:02.110 --> 00:03:04.170
There's 6,000 conviviums
around the country.

00:03:04.170 --> 00:03:07.150
People get together
and prepare local foods

00:03:07.150 --> 00:03:09.520
and eat them with friends.

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:12.210
Also, of course, having
a more vegetarian diet

00:03:12.210 --> 00:03:14.880
or eating lower on the
food chain, of course,

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:19.300
has less greenhouse gas
emissions, another advantage.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:21.670
There's also slow
money, which looks

00:03:21.670 --> 00:03:24.300
at how we're
investing our capital.

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:26.310
Is it being invested
in big agribusiness,

00:03:26.310 --> 00:03:29.330
for example, that contributes
a lot of chemicals

00:03:29.330 --> 00:03:34.330
and monocultures, or is it going
toward sustainable agriculture?

00:03:34.330 --> 00:03:38.140
The issue of work life
balance is actually

00:03:38.140 --> 00:03:42.810
tied into the culture
of "fast and more"

00:03:42.810 --> 00:03:45.340
and the response to it.

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:47.660
So I know here at
Google there's been

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:50.130
a lot of efforts to have
flextime and other things

00:03:50.130 --> 00:03:52.571
that you're experimenting with.

00:03:52.571 --> 00:03:55.070
You probably know that Carlos
Slim, the world's richest man,

00:03:55.070 --> 00:03:57.570
called for a three day work week
recently, and has repeated it

00:03:57.570 --> 00:03:58.150
many times.

00:03:58.150 --> 00:03:59.350
He says, it will happen.

00:03:59.350 --> 00:04:02.420
He says most recently that he's
realized through his career

00:04:02.420 --> 00:04:05.600
that, really, life is about
more than just working.

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:07.450
And actually you can
get a ton of efficiency

00:04:07.450 --> 00:04:11.310
into these three 11-hour
days, and then have four days

00:04:11.310 --> 00:04:15.490
to refresh yourself,
have creative pursuits

00:04:15.490 --> 00:04:19.100
and come back to work
much more changed.

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:21.154
So I don't know
if you know-- does

00:04:21.154 --> 00:04:23.950
this have a little
pointer on it?

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:24.580
Yeah, it does.

00:04:24.580 --> 00:04:28.280
So the United States,
actually, is the lowest amount

00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:30.250
of leave in the
industrialized world.

00:04:30.250 --> 00:04:33.290
We only have 12 days.

00:04:33.290 --> 00:04:36.800
And there's this whole Take
Back Your Time movement.

00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:40.500
Who's heard of Take Back Your
Time day, October 24 each year?

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:43.347
It's the day when Europeans
could stop working

00:04:43.347 --> 00:04:45.430
and Americans have to work
to the end of the year,

00:04:45.430 --> 00:04:49.190
because they get nine
weeks more vacation

00:04:49.190 --> 00:04:50.686
than we do on average a year.

00:04:50.686 --> 00:04:51.560
That's how much more.

00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:53.530
And these are other
industrialized countries.

00:04:53.530 --> 00:04:56.930
So it's a way of saying, I mean,
even medieval peasants worked

00:04:56.930 --> 00:04:58.950
less than we did, in
terms of number of hours.

00:04:58.950 --> 00:05:02.330
If you look at how
productivity from 1970-2010

00:05:02.330 --> 00:05:04.630
has actually gone
four folds, including

00:05:04.630 --> 00:05:07.520
using the kind of tools
that you're making, and yet

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:08.510
our hours have gone up.

00:05:08.510 --> 00:05:10.650
Why is it that the
average hour of work

00:05:10.650 --> 00:05:12.780
is four times more
productive, and yet we're

00:05:12.780 --> 00:05:14.250
working more hours,
and much more

00:05:14.250 --> 00:05:18.510
than are industrialized
counterparts?

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:20.239
Another sort of model
that's out there,

00:05:20.239 --> 00:05:22.530
that you may have heard of--
who's heard of transition?

00:05:22.530 --> 00:05:25.160
Transition towns?

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:26.470
Very few of you.

00:05:26.470 --> 00:05:28.770
Well, basically, the
idea is that we're

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:31.830
in this era of kind
of fossil fuels

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:37.550
and we need to get
to more solar, winds.

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:40.480
We're also in an era
of mass organization,

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:42.570
and why not look more at small?

00:05:42.570 --> 00:05:43.627
So small is beautiful.

00:05:43.627 --> 00:05:45.210
Getting back to
models of organization

00:05:45.210 --> 00:05:47.510
at the neighborhood level,
the community level.

00:05:47.510 --> 00:05:48.810
So in New York City,
for example there's

00:05:48.810 --> 00:05:51.393
transition neighborhoods in New
York, where you're looking at,

00:05:51.393 --> 00:05:54.410
like, how we source our
energy for that neighborhood,

00:05:54.410 --> 00:05:55.830
where we get our food.

00:05:55.830 --> 00:05:57.830
How can you source
it more effectively?

00:05:57.830 --> 00:06:00.650
So all over the world, and more
so in England than anywhere,

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:02.980
there are these transition
communities really figuring

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:04.780
out how to be self
sustainable in a world

00:06:04.780 --> 00:06:09.010
where fossil fuels become
less and less viable

00:06:09.010 --> 00:06:11.060
in terms of climate change.

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:13.560
And this is an example of
a sort of transition town

00:06:13.560 --> 00:06:15.170
type of communities
and architecture,

00:06:15.170 --> 00:06:16.210
designing with nature.

00:06:16.210 --> 00:06:18.960
Biomimicry, mimicking
the way nature

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:21.120
creates and creating our
architecture that way,

00:06:21.120 --> 00:06:25.160
even in cities-- how we
can look at human well

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:29.100
being as the basis for how
we're organizing things

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:31.359
and create around that.

00:06:31.359 --> 00:06:33.150
Even walking around
here in Kendall Square,

00:06:33.150 --> 00:06:35.680
it's beautiful, MIT is
very nice, all of this,

00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:37.727
but what if we
had it even nicer?

00:06:37.727 --> 00:06:39.310
What if there were
more buildings that

00:06:39.310 --> 00:06:43.220
were kind of shaped
around nature?

00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:46.350
There's the whole environmental
psychology, or eco psychology

00:06:46.350 --> 00:06:50.020
area that's out now, that
they're looking at the fact

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:52.300
that human's
relationship with nature

00:06:52.300 --> 00:06:54.660
is part of our emotional
and social well being.

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:57.220
And when we cut that cord,
we're bound to feel depressed.

00:06:57.220 --> 00:06:59.630
And a lot of the kind of
neuroses and bipolar disorders

00:06:59.630 --> 00:07:01.838
and everything is actually
tied to this disconnection

00:07:01.838 --> 00:07:02.490
with nature.

00:07:02.490 --> 00:07:05.110
E. O. Wilson talks about this
in his biomimicry theory.

00:07:05.110 --> 00:07:09.425
So these types of transition and
green architecture activities

00:07:09.425 --> 00:07:10.550
actually help that as well.

00:07:10.550 --> 00:07:13.290
So there's all these things
that are in this great turning.

00:07:13.290 --> 00:07:16.316
Unfortunately, there is this
culture of fast and more.

00:07:16.316 --> 00:07:18.190
And let me just clarify
that when I say slow,

00:07:18.190 --> 00:07:19.856
I'm not talking about
always going slow.

00:07:19.856 --> 00:07:21.356
I'm talking about
being self-paced--

00:07:21.356 --> 00:07:23.522
being able to determine the
rhythm of your own life,

00:07:23.522 --> 00:07:25.270
having the control
of that and to be

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:27.030
able to vary the
rhythm, the tempo

00:07:27.030 --> 00:07:29.710
gusto, the right speed,
as they say in music.

00:07:29.710 --> 00:07:34.420
So we're in this system
where, unfortunately,

00:07:34.420 --> 00:07:37.530
the industrial model
of growth is leading

00:07:37.530 --> 00:07:39.360
to this type of water shortage.

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:42.460
Last week in San Paolo they
had massive water shortages,

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:44.510
which caused riots.

00:07:44.510 --> 00:07:47.600
This is caused by climate
change and deforestation.

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:50.030
As you know in
China, for example,

00:07:50.030 --> 00:07:52.080
the pollution from
coastal China spreads

00:07:52.080 --> 00:07:53.200
across the rest of Asia.

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:56.140
Their environmental problems
are not respecting boundaries.

00:07:56.140 --> 00:07:58.530
And we have, in
Bolivia, where I'm

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:01.819
currently living-- we left New
York for Bolivia last year,

00:08:01.819 --> 00:08:04.360
and that's another story which
I'll tell you about-- but this

00:08:04.360 --> 00:08:08.650
is the example of deep poverty
interacting with cycles

00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:13.980
of slash and burn agriculture,
cutting down the rain forests.

00:08:13.980 --> 00:08:18.260
And at the same time
huge monocropping.

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:19.930
So I talked about
slow money, investing

00:08:19.930 --> 00:08:21.510
in sustainable agriculture.

00:08:21.510 --> 00:08:23.780
When you just have your
investment in-- this

00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:26.400
is Archer Daniel the
Midlands, ADM in Bolivia,

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:28.970
cutting down huge amounts of
rain forest for our grains

00:08:28.970 --> 00:08:29.680
and so on.

00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:32.990
So I mean, you really have to
look at what we're doing here

00:08:32.990 --> 00:08:35.539
and how it's felt
around the world.

00:08:35.539 --> 00:08:38.350
For example, this is the
border of Bolivia and Brazil,

00:08:38.350 --> 00:08:40.919
where we are right now.

00:08:40.919 --> 00:08:44.637
This is Bolivia--
Bolivia, Bolivia, Bolivia.

00:08:44.637 --> 00:08:46.220
And as you can see,
the Brazilian side

00:08:46.220 --> 00:08:53.020
is totally cut down for
soy, for chia-- the new crop

00:08:53.020 --> 00:08:56.210
that everyone's growing, for
cattle ranching and so on.

00:08:56.210 --> 00:08:59.780
Bolivia is still that
more uninhabited boundary,

00:08:59.780 --> 00:09:02.775
but the same process
is coming there.

00:09:02.775 --> 00:09:04.650
Luckily, however, there
is no global warming.

00:09:04.650 --> 00:09:07.770
Do you see this?

00:09:07.770 --> 00:09:10.810
Yeah, they just confused
Fahrenheit and Celsius.

00:09:10.810 --> 00:09:13.560
There's no problem with global
warming-- not really, of course

00:09:13.560 --> 00:09:14.070
there is.

00:09:16.475 --> 00:09:18.100
I don't have to talk
to you about this.

00:09:18.100 --> 00:09:20.058
I'm sure everyone here
knows about the problem.

00:09:20.058 --> 00:09:22.130
I mean, just walk outside today.

00:09:22.130 --> 00:09:24.050
Or look at last winter,
how extreme it was.

00:09:24.050 --> 00:09:26.070
All of these changes
that we're seeing,

00:09:26.070 --> 00:09:30.380
even here in New England,
is very, very clearly

00:09:30.380 --> 00:09:31.967
even felt more
strongly in places

00:09:31.967 --> 00:09:33.050
like Greenland or Bolivia.

00:09:33.050 --> 00:09:35.630
This is Bolivia
Chacaltaya Mountain.

00:09:35.630 --> 00:09:37.780
This was Bolivia's
only ski resort.

00:09:37.780 --> 00:09:40.630
In just a matter of
decades it's gone

00:09:40.630 --> 00:09:42.996
from being a glacier to nothing.

00:09:42.996 --> 00:09:44.870
So they had to close
the ski resort recently.

00:09:44.870 --> 00:09:47.192
It doesn't exist
anymore, because like all

00:09:47.192 --> 00:09:49.150
the other glaciers in
Bolivia, they're melting.

00:09:49.150 --> 00:09:51.720
And it's affecting the water
supply for millions of people.

00:09:51.720 --> 00:09:52.995
So these are the
types of issues that

00:09:52.995 --> 00:09:54.703
have led even countries
like the Maldives

00:09:54.703 --> 00:09:57.270
to have their cabinet
meetings underwater.

00:09:57.270 --> 00:09:59.044
This is the president
of the Maldives,

00:09:59.044 --> 00:10:01.210
and they're actually signing
legislation under water

00:10:01.210 --> 00:10:04.690
to show that their country
is about to go under.

00:10:04.690 --> 00:10:07.624
And in my own city in New York,
of course, Hurricane Sandy

00:10:07.624 --> 00:10:09.290
and the effect that
it had, our building

00:10:09.290 --> 00:10:12.120
was out of power for two weeks
and everything was flooded.

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:14.170
There was environmental
refugees in New York.

00:10:14.170 --> 00:10:17.045
My students at NYU were in
the Bronx like in shanties.

00:10:17.045 --> 00:10:17.920
It was just terrible.

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:20.790
For two weeks, we
were feeling it there.

00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:23.090
And of course, a lot of this
is tied in with, sort of,

00:10:23.090 --> 00:10:25.717
subsidies for oil and gas and
hardly anything for renewables.

00:10:25.717 --> 00:10:27.550
But we don't have to
go into that in detail.

00:10:31.290 --> 00:10:35.670
So all this anecdotal stuff and
all these different examples

00:10:35.670 --> 00:10:39.400
is tied into a very
stark fact, and that's

00:10:39.400 --> 00:10:43.330
this-- that our
average footprint

00:10:43.330 --> 00:10:46.200
of the average American
is five planets.

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:47.800
This is UN scientists
who say that it

00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:50.650
would take five
planets of resources

00:10:50.650 --> 00:10:53.720
if everyone lived at our
level of consumption.

00:10:53.720 --> 00:10:57.480
That is an extreme
point of view.

00:10:57.480 --> 00:11:02.270
And the reason is because of
what we call over development.

00:11:02.270 --> 00:11:05.310
So there's development,
and then there's

00:11:05.310 --> 00:11:08.170
under development, which is
like maybe 20% of humanity's

00:11:08.170 --> 00:11:15.060
underdeveloped, starving,
in war zones without enough.

00:11:15.060 --> 00:11:17.500
60% of humanity is
developed, that's

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:21.385
subsistence, agriculture,
living with enough.

00:11:21.385 --> 00:11:22.760
And then there's
overdevelopment.

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:26.260
Overdevelopment is
taking it too far.

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:28.620
And the kind of mega diversity
that you see in a place

00:11:28.620 --> 00:11:30.950
like Bolivia, unfortunately,
is turning into this.

00:11:30.950 --> 00:11:33.000
I just recently
found these photos.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.730
This is the new mall in Santa
Cruz, the first mall in Bolivia

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:37.347
that's come.

00:11:37.347 --> 00:11:39.680
And it's just amazing to see
the chains, like McDonald's

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:41.138
and Hard Rock and
everything coming

00:11:41.138 --> 00:11:43.660
into the city and
this enormous mall.

00:11:46.600 --> 00:11:48.430
It's really, to
me, quite shocking

00:11:48.430 --> 00:11:50.670
because this is the
Bolivia that I know,

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:52.990
and this is where
we're going with it.

00:11:52.990 --> 00:11:55.950
So I'm talking about a big
philosophical issue that

00:11:55.950 --> 00:11:58.170
actually led me to be
kind of depressed after 10

00:11:58.170 --> 00:11:59.660
years of working.

00:11:59.660 --> 00:12:02.565
Yeah, we had prize winning
projects from the JFK school

00:12:02.565 --> 00:12:04.815
in rain forests in Bolivia,
with carbon sequestration.

00:12:04.815 --> 00:12:06.070
We had all kinds of
incredible things

00:12:06.070 --> 00:12:07.560
we were doing that
were successful,

00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:10.910
but with five
planets of resources,

00:12:10.910 --> 00:12:13.020
sometimes it felt
like it was in vain.

00:12:13.020 --> 00:12:15.215
So after 10 years of
working abroad-- just

00:12:15.215 --> 00:12:20.330
to tell you a personal story--
I came back to the US in 2007,

00:12:20.330 --> 00:12:23.430
and I ended up
living in this cabin.

00:12:23.430 --> 00:12:26.180
It was a 12 foot by
12 foot cabin off

00:12:26.180 --> 00:12:27.440
grid in North Carolina.

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:31.620
It's a permaculture farm.

00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:35.570
And can you picture what 12
foot by 12 foot is, like how big

00:12:35.570 --> 00:12:36.417
that is?

00:12:36.417 --> 00:12:38.250
AUDIENCE: Less than
what you're standing on.

00:12:38.250 --> 00:12:38.630
BILL POWERS: Right.

00:12:38.630 --> 00:12:40.462
So maybe-- why don't
just do a little thing

00:12:40.462 --> 00:12:41.670
just so we can understand it.

00:12:41.670 --> 00:12:43.275
Can you guys, can
you four stand up

00:12:43.275 --> 00:12:45.500
here and try to arrange
yourself 12 by 12.

00:12:45.500 --> 00:12:46.920
See if you can do that.

