00:12:52.424 --> 00:12:53.870
AUDIENCE: No, [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:53.870 --> 00:12:55.352
BILL POWERS: Too big, right!

00:12:55.352 --> 00:12:57.060
I'm probably going
off camera, but let me

00:12:57.060 --> 00:12:58.435
just come down
for a second here.

00:12:58.435 --> 00:13:00.395
So like this is
basically-- yeah,

00:13:00.395 --> 00:13:01.770
maybe you would
have to be here--

00:13:01.770 --> 00:13:04.240
but basically, this was the
12 bu 12 and what it was like.

00:13:04.240 --> 00:13:04.950
So this is where I lived.

00:13:04.950 --> 00:13:05.490
Yeah, that's perfect.

00:13:05.490 --> 00:13:06.120
Thank you.

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:06.310
OK.

00:13:06.310 --> 00:13:07.726
So just to give
you a visual here,

00:13:07.726 --> 00:13:09.890
I would come into
the house, like this.

00:13:09.890 --> 00:13:14.640
And there was one bed up
in a loft, a little place

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:18.751
to cook with natural gas
here, and a rocking chair

00:13:18.751 --> 00:13:21.000
over here in the corner, and
the entrance and candles.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:21.666
And that was it.

00:13:21.666 --> 00:13:24.960
And this belongs to a physician
in North Carolina, who actually

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:27.372
downsized from a big house
and moved into this thing.

00:13:27.372 --> 00:13:29.080
And she's been living
in it for 10 years,

00:13:29.080 --> 00:13:31.130
and she invited me to
live there for a season.

00:13:31.130 --> 00:13:34.365
So you can imagine being
in the middle of American

00:13:34.365 --> 00:13:38.750
and living in this tiny 12
by 12, kind of blew me away.

00:13:38.750 --> 00:13:40.900
I was there, actually, spring.

00:13:40.900 --> 00:13:42.770
It was like end of
winter into spring.

00:13:42.770 --> 00:13:45.890
So even when it's cold,
there's no wood burning stove.

00:13:45.890 --> 00:13:47.240
You use more layers.

00:13:47.240 --> 00:13:49.430
You know, homo sapiens,
we're a strong species.

00:13:49.430 --> 00:13:50.967
We adapt to lots
of environments.

00:13:50.967 --> 00:13:53.300
And that's what I also realized
working around the world

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:55.232
and living in this
12 by 12, especially,

00:13:55.232 --> 00:13:56.440
was that you can adapt to it.

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:57.300
So this just gives
you a little--

00:13:57.300 --> 00:13:58.880
thank you for showing something.

00:13:58.880 --> 00:13:59.130
AUDIENCE: No heat?

00:13:59.130 --> 00:14:00.350
BILL POWERS: No heat at all.

00:14:00.350 --> 00:14:01.933
It is North Carolina,
of course, so it

00:14:01.933 --> 00:14:04.747
has to be adapted to whatever
environment you're in.

00:14:04.747 --> 00:14:06.330
And just to give you
some more images,

00:14:06.330 --> 00:14:09.920
like this is the model that
this physician, Doctor Jackie

00:14:09.920 --> 00:14:10.820
Benton, is modeling.

00:14:10.820 --> 00:14:16.560
So there is the 12 by 12, which
only costs $7,000 to build.

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:20.760
$10,000 for her land, two acres
full of permaculture paradise

00:14:20.760 --> 00:14:24.130
of 200 species of crops
and so on, a little no name

00:14:24.130 --> 00:14:25.720
creek over here.

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:28.907
It's this type of a design
with rainwater catchments.

00:14:28.907 --> 00:14:30.990
Yeah, everything off the
grid and she lives there.

00:14:34.829 --> 00:14:36.370
And these are the
types of neighbors,

00:14:36.370 --> 00:14:38.162
you know, you get all
this organic produce.

00:14:38.162 --> 00:14:40.703
It was sort of like what I was
used to experiencing in places

00:14:40.703 --> 00:14:42.620
like Bolivia, but in
the middle of the US.

00:14:42.620 --> 00:14:48.220
They're designing around open
space and intensive agriculture

00:14:48.220 --> 00:14:51.410
agroforestry, smaller scale.

00:14:54.680 --> 00:14:58.400
Just to show you what this
is in terms of the data,

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:03.160
living 12 by 12, or
living more simply,

00:15:03.160 --> 00:15:06.580
it does actually bring joy
because, actually, happiness

00:15:06.580 --> 00:15:10.585
and well-being increases
very quickly if you're poor,

00:15:10.585 --> 00:15:12.782
if you're very poor--
like $9,000 in GDP.

00:15:12.782 --> 00:15:13.990
But then it kind of plateaus.

00:15:13.990 --> 00:15:16.930
So this is the basic idea,
that happiness, of course,

00:15:16.930 --> 00:15:20.832
it goes up with money, but
then it plateaus is the idea.

00:15:20.832 --> 00:15:23.290
So when I came back to New York
City after living in the 12

00:15:23.290 --> 00:15:26.060
by 12, I found that
our townhouse that we

00:15:26.060 --> 00:15:29.150
own in Queens, my wife
and I, was just too big.

00:15:29.150 --> 00:15:31.190
It was 2000 square feet.

00:15:31.190 --> 00:15:33.035
So we moved to this
tiny apartment.

00:15:33.035 --> 00:15:35.160
This is just examples--
this is not our apartment--

00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:38.360
but of a micro apartment in
Manhattan, 340 square feet.

00:15:38.360 --> 00:15:40.509
So it was like two 12
by 12s put together.

00:15:40.509 --> 00:15:42.050
And we experimented
for a year living

00:15:42.050 --> 00:15:45.990
very minimalist in the belly
of the beast, New York City.

00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:48.480
And it was actually
quite fascinating

00:15:48.480 --> 00:15:52.890
because we started to
see our micro apartment--

00:15:52.890 --> 00:15:55.140
and by the way, this is part
of Bloomberg's initiative

00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:58.080
for everyone to live in smaller
apartments, lower rents and so

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:01.450
on-- we thought of it as a ship.

00:16:01.450 --> 00:16:03.079
We designed it as a ship.

00:16:03.079 --> 00:16:04.120
Everything had its place.

00:16:04.120 --> 00:16:05.920
There was no more clutter.

00:16:05.920 --> 00:16:07.410
We just felt, in
some ways, happier

00:16:07.410 --> 00:16:08.910
because we knew where everything
was and we had less stuff

00:16:08.910 --> 00:16:10.140
to worry about.

00:16:10.140 --> 00:16:13.440
So there was some
advantages to minimalizing

00:16:13.440 --> 00:16:18.270
and you know, lower rents.

00:16:18.270 --> 00:16:21.977
I also reduced my working
hours by a lot, basically

00:16:21.977 --> 00:16:23.810
to the three hour work
week that Carlos Slim

00:16:23.810 --> 00:16:26.740
is calling for--
three day work week.

00:16:26.740 --> 00:16:31.545
And I just think that these
technologies that you all

00:16:31.545 --> 00:16:34.450
are involved in are beautiful
things if they're your tool

00:16:34.450 --> 00:16:35.610
and you're not their fool.

00:16:35.610 --> 00:16:39.110
If you're actually using
them for liberating yourself

00:16:39.110 --> 00:16:41.610
from the work and
spend treadmill,

00:16:41.610 --> 00:16:44.480
from giving yourself
more free time

00:16:44.480 --> 00:16:47.990
to enjoy your family,
friends, nature, your hobbies,

00:16:47.990 --> 00:16:49.312
what you love to do.

00:16:49.312 --> 00:16:50.770
Think of things
that you love to do

00:16:50.770 --> 00:16:53.144
and imagine doing them five
times more than you are right

00:16:53.144 --> 00:16:54.316
now.

00:16:54.316 --> 00:16:56.670
I hope this is not too
subversive a thought

00:16:56.670 --> 00:17:00.080
for being in the office
on a Monday morning.

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:02.720
But the idea is that I was
working, honestly, a two

00:17:02.720 --> 00:17:05.750
day work week for the
good part of that year

00:17:05.750 --> 00:17:09.619
that we lived slow,
and just enjoying

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:10.880
so much more about the city.

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:13.010
And just working smarter
instead of harder

00:17:13.010 --> 00:17:15.480
and it was this whole
other philosophy.

00:17:15.480 --> 00:17:18.540
Really, just to switch it, what
it comes down to, in some ways,

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:22.079
is a Greek word
that Aristotle used

00:17:22.079 --> 00:17:24.960
to talk about a lot,
which is eudaimonia.

00:17:24.960 --> 00:17:26.558
It's "what is the best life."

00:17:26.558 --> 00:17:28.349
That's what the Greeks
would struggle with,

00:17:28.349 --> 00:17:29.190
and that's what
we don't struggle

00:17:29.190 --> 00:17:30.590
with enough these days.

00:17:30.590 --> 00:17:33.390
It's like, what is
the economy for?

00:17:33.390 --> 00:17:34.900
What is work for?

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:37.410
How do we create this best life?

00:17:37.410 --> 00:17:39.720
I'm not going to give you
my entire graduate course

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:41.850
in economic development
right now, but just

00:17:41.850 --> 00:17:45.840
to let you know that there are
various perspectives on what

00:17:45.840 --> 00:17:48.010
development is.

00:17:48.010 --> 00:17:49.460
OK?

00:17:49.460 --> 00:17:52.910
What we think is development
is growth economics.

00:17:52.910 --> 00:17:54.874
That's the dominant paradigm.

00:17:54.874 --> 00:17:56.290
And then there's
a hybrid of that,

00:17:56.290 --> 00:17:58.970
which is the human development
paradigm, like the HDI

00:17:58.970 --> 00:18:01.867
index, which says, oh we should
bring people into development.

00:18:01.867 --> 00:18:03.450
It's not just about
growing economies.

00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:05.030
We have to think about people.

00:18:05.030 --> 00:18:08.050
But there are these
wonderful critiques,

00:18:08.050 --> 00:18:11.380
innovators in theory and
practice and development

00:18:11.380 --> 00:18:16.250
who are saying, biocentrism,
post development-- I recommend

00:18:16.250 --> 00:18:17.400
Arturo Escobar.

00:18:17.400 --> 00:18:19.450
He has a book called
"Encountering Developments",

00:18:19.450 --> 00:18:20.116
which is genius.

00:18:23.710 --> 00:18:28.160
David Abrams' work on "The
Spell of the Sensuous",

00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:31.540
more biocentric points of views.

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:34.130
Escobar, for example,
this anthropologist

00:18:34.130 --> 00:18:38.560
says we need to look at
the West, our own culture,

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:39.870
as exotic.

00:18:39.870 --> 00:18:42.600
Very difficult to do,
but this is exotic,

00:18:42.600 --> 00:18:45.302
this kind of deforestation,
this is exotic.

00:18:45.302 --> 00:18:46.760
So there's the
country of Nacirema,

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:47.888
do you know where that is?

00:18:47.888 --> 00:18:49.262
Nacirema, have
you heard of this?

00:18:49.262 --> 00:18:50.875
AUDIENCE: Backwards America.

00:18:50.875 --> 00:18:51.750
BILL POWERS: Exactly.

00:18:51.750 --> 00:18:54.300
It's American spelled backwards.

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:55.930
So you just reverse
the way you look

00:18:55.930 --> 00:18:57.710
at our own culture for a second.

00:18:57.710 --> 00:19:01.930
It looks very different.

00:19:01.930 --> 00:19:05.234
This we talked about,
biocentrism and expanding

00:19:05.234 --> 00:19:06.525
emotional connection to nature.

00:19:09.430 --> 00:19:17.660
Very key ideas of-- even when
you think about your work

00:19:17.660 --> 00:19:21.290
at Google, or how you
organize your time and so

00:19:21.290 --> 00:19:23.650
on, is it possible
for a second to look

00:19:23.650 --> 00:19:25.820
at things from the
perspective of other species,

00:19:25.820 --> 00:19:29.550
not just an anthropocentric
point of view of how this

00:19:29.550 --> 00:19:32.940
benefits our species, but
how it benefits the whole?

00:19:32.940 --> 00:19:35.460
And you immediately have this
shift in your consciousness,

00:19:35.460 --> 00:19:38.890
where you just feel more
aligned with the world.

00:19:38.890 --> 00:19:39.800
You feel happier.

00:19:39.800 --> 00:19:42.940
You feel like what you're
doing is more inclusive.

00:19:42.940 --> 00:19:45.540
I'm not saying you
have to become a vegan,

00:19:45.540 --> 00:19:48.350
and I'm not a vegetarian myself.

00:19:48.350 --> 00:19:51.270
But I'm just saying that
there's this way of seeing

00:19:51.270 --> 00:19:53.540
the world that's very
different from how we see it.

00:19:53.540 --> 00:19:59.240
And these more critical
development theorists

00:19:59.240 --> 00:20:00.280
are pointing that way.

00:20:03.480 --> 00:20:06.150
You are now entering
a stress free zone.

00:20:06.150 --> 00:20:09.530
So the point of this
is that-- I just want

00:20:09.530 --> 00:20:12.450
to share most recently--
we, my wife and I,

00:20:12.450 --> 00:20:14.740
took another kind
of experimental step

00:20:14.740 --> 00:20:17.101
because we're always
kind of life hacking,

00:20:17.101 --> 00:20:19.600
figuring out how to do things
differently and experimenting.

00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:21.016
Because you only
live once and you

00:20:21.016 --> 00:20:23.210
might as well push
your boundaries.

00:20:23.210 --> 00:20:24.750
So we actually
moved from New York

00:20:24.750 --> 00:20:26.350
after we were there
for five years.

00:20:26.350 --> 00:20:28.070
We moved down to Bolivia.

00:20:28.070 --> 00:20:31.910
So now I'm coming to
you here from a town

00:20:31.910 --> 00:20:34.320
of 4,000 people,
where the Andes meets

00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:36.800
the Amazon in central Bolivia.

00:20:36.800 --> 00:20:39.220
It's a beautiful town
called called Samaipata.

00:20:39.220 --> 00:20:44.330
It's where the Andes
elbows into the Amazon.

00:20:44.330 --> 00:20:47.570
So you see it's like
forested-- this is Samaipata--

00:20:47.570 --> 00:20:52.130
but also there's
mountainous climate.

00:20:52.130 --> 00:20:56.129
And there's people
from 30 countries here.

00:20:56.129 --> 00:20:57.670
A lot of people are
innovating around

00:20:57.670 --> 00:20:59.980
different aspects of
what I'm talking about.

00:20:59.980 --> 00:21:03.250
Slow money, slow
living, permaculture,

00:21:03.250 --> 00:21:05.660
which is combining
architecture with landscape

00:21:05.660 --> 00:21:10.560
design in harmony with
nature, all these ideas.

00:21:10.560 --> 00:21:15.110
And it's a very
beautiful place to be.

00:21:15.110 --> 00:21:17.270
Also right now,
in Bolivia, do you

00:21:17.270 --> 00:21:20.430
know that they have the Law
of Mother Earth as their macro

00:21:20.430 --> 00:21:21.050
law?

00:21:21.050 --> 00:21:22.210
It sounds kind of crazy.

00:21:22.210 --> 00:21:26.000
But the idea is that the earth
has nine indelible rights,

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:27.920
and you can sue
corporations for violating

00:21:27.920 --> 00:21:31.600
the rights of Pachamama,
as they call it.

00:21:31.600 --> 00:21:33.790
So for them the
most important thing

00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:37.730
is Pachamama, because
all life comes from that.

00:21:37.730 --> 00:21:42.370
And so the right to life and
to exist, vital functions

00:21:42.370 --> 00:21:45.080
of the ecosystem, all
of that is legislated.

00:21:45.080 --> 00:21:47.010
Now, they're not perfect
in implementing it,

00:21:47.010 --> 00:21:49.666
but they do have this new
framework that they're saying.

00:21:49.666 --> 00:21:52.290
So a lot of what we're doing at
the local level in a transition

00:21:52.290 --> 00:21:55.584
town relates to the
national policy.

00:21:55.584 --> 00:21:57.500
And Bolivia is kind of
basing some other stuff

00:21:57.500 --> 00:22:00.041
around the fact that-- this is
another way of looking at what

00:22:00.041 --> 00:22:02.540
I showed you before--
as personal income

00:22:02.540 --> 00:22:07.050
increases, the percentage of
people identifying themselves

00:22:07.050 --> 00:22:08.880
as very happy stays the same.

00:22:08.880 --> 00:22:11.790
This is in the United
States over the years.

00:22:11.790 --> 00:22:17.110
So they're saying, OK well
if that's the case then

00:22:17.110 --> 00:22:20.390
how do you have a
living well policy?

00:22:20.390 --> 00:22:21.970
And that's, by the
way, what Bolivia

00:22:21.970 --> 00:22:24.100
has as their other sort
of norm is living well.

00:22:24.100 --> 00:22:25.058
Have you heard of this?

00:22:25.058 --> 00:22:27.910
Living well, vivir
bien, in Spanish?

00:22:27.910 --> 00:22:31.280
What's our philosophy in the US?

00:22:31.280 --> 00:22:32.350
Is it vivir bien?

00:22:32.350 --> 00:22:34.730
Is it living well, or
what would you say it is?

00:22:34.730 --> 00:22:36.010
What's the dominant ethos?

00:22:36.010 --> 00:22:37.750
AUDIENCE: Work hard, play hard.

00:22:37.750 --> 00:22:39.210
BILL POWERS: Work
hard, play hard?

00:22:39.210 --> 00:22:44.460
That's probably Google's ethos,
but what about the American--

00:22:44.460 --> 00:22:46.690
maybe work hard, play hard--
but what would you say?

00:22:46.690 --> 00:22:47.460
More.

00:22:47.460 --> 00:22:48.050
Yeah, more.

00:22:48.050 --> 00:22:49.200
Better, right?

00:22:49.200 --> 00:22:50.510
Living better.

00:22:50.510 --> 00:22:54.386
In Bolivia, it's Quechua,
Aymara, Guarani, Chiquitano,

00:22:54.386 --> 00:22:55.510
it's an indigenous country.

00:22:55.510 --> 00:22:57.530
It's 75% indigenous.

00:22:57.530 --> 00:23:00.660
Their philosophy is living well.

00:23:00.660 --> 00:23:04.160
So you get to a certain
point of development,

00:23:04.160 --> 00:23:06.400
like whatever, you know
like the other graph

00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:08.066
where you get to
certain point, and then

00:23:08.066 --> 00:23:09.569
you have a steady state economy.

00:23:09.569 --> 00:23:11.360
That's what Herman Daly
has been telling us

00:23:11.360 --> 00:23:13.659
for years-- this
famous economist-- that

00:23:13.659 --> 00:23:15.700
just like the human body
grows to a certain level

00:23:15.700 --> 00:23:18.275
and then stops growing
and maintains equilibrium

00:23:18.275 --> 00:23:20.411
and health, so too
should our economy grow

00:23:20.411 --> 00:23:21.910
to a certain level
and then not have

00:23:21.910 --> 00:23:24.100
to have this hyper
development path.

00:23:24.100 --> 00:23:26.360
So Bolivia is playing
with that creative edge

00:23:26.360 --> 00:23:30.570
of how to do an economy
at a national level

00:23:30.570 --> 00:23:33.850
according to living
well and not better.

00:23:33.850 --> 00:23:38.460
It's an interesting thing.

00:23:38.460 --> 00:23:41.370
Just to show you, this is our
house that we just finished.

00:23:41.370 --> 00:23:44.650
Small house, we used some
of the minimalism design.

00:23:44.650 --> 00:23:47.420
This whole house we built out
of adobe from our own land.

00:23:47.420 --> 00:23:49.500
This is where the
adobe was dug up.

00:23:49.500 --> 00:23:51.800
It's thermal mass 40 cm.

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:54.560
It maintains 22 degrees Celsius
all year round with no heating

00:23:54.560 --> 00:23:57.030
or cooling because of the adobe.

00:23:57.030 --> 00:23:59.030
There was no embedded
carbon because it was just

00:23:59.030 --> 00:24:01.380
baked by the sun right
there on our property.

00:24:01.380 --> 00:24:02.480
And it's beautiful.

00:24:02.480 --> 00:24:04.500
We have beautiful
windows and double doors,

00:24:04.500 --> 00:24:07.250
but it's minimalist,
beautiful and ecological.

00:24:07.250 --> 00:24:10.400
Like all of our waste is
reused, it goes to banana trees.

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:13.260
The sewage goes into a
tank that gets filtered

00:24:13.260 --> 00:24:15.070
through different
plants and everything.

00:24:15.070 --> 00:24:19.670
And the grey water is
going to a composting area.

00:24:19.670 --> 00:24:22.430
So this is what we're kind
of experimenting with there,

00:24:22.430 --> 00:24:24.430
another example of
ecological architecture.

00:24:28.010 --> 00:24:30.740
I like this cartoon.

00:24:30.740 --> 00:24:34.660
So you know, what if we created
a better world for nothing?

00:24:34.660 --> 00:24:36.540
That's almost like
the best you can say.

00:24:36.540 --> 00:24:40.110
I think we need to just keep
pushing our boundaries, just

00:24:40.110 --> 00:24:43.600
to sum up what I've
been talking about.

00:24:43.600 --> 00:24:45.800
Getting more creative,
keeping in mind

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:48.940
the Earth's biophysical
limits in our decisions,

00:24:48.940 --> 00:24:51.660
having a more ecocentric
point of view,

00:24:51.660 --> 00:24:54.312
trying to find more happiness
and joy in work life balance,

00:24:54.312 --> 00:24:55.520
all of this is tied together.

00:24:55.520 --> 00:24:58.310
All of it's tied to the big
challenge of our time, which

00:24:58.310 --> 00:25:01.590
is confronting this
culture of fast and more

00:25:01.590 --> 00:25:05.070
that's contributing to ecocide,
or the destruction of life's

00:25:05.070 --> 00:25:09.520
vital processes, and
finding new system.

00:25:09.520 --> 00:25:13.600
A system that's based more in
principles of a steady state

00:25:13.600 --> 00:25:18.800
economy, of transition towns,
of a slower, saner, fit

00:25:18.800 --> 00:25:21.060
for the future type of a life.

00:25:21.060 --> 00:25:23.880
And I think every single
one of us has a role.

00:25:23.880 --> 00:25:27.220
Like in this room,
whatever you're

00:25:27.220 --> 00:25:30.740
doing here or in your
civic organizations

00:25:30.740 --> 00:25:34.080
in your free time or whatever,
you have a role in this change.

00:25:34.080 --> 00:25:37.370
And I would just
encourage you to think

00:25:37.370 --> 00:25:41.390
about what that role could be.

00:25:41.390 --> 00:25:45.400
And I hope that you read
my book "New Slow City",

00:25:45.400 --> 00:25:49.290
which Jonathan was nice
enough to get for all of you.

00:25:49.290 --> 00:25:53.870
The book is not really lecturing
as to what you should do,

00:25:53.870 --> 00:25:56.590
but I think it's opening
up a lot of questions

00:25:56.590 --> 00:25:59.310
about ways that we
can push ourselves

00:25:59.310 --> 00:26:03.720
to think about these things more
deeply, enjoy life more fully,

00:26:03.720 --> 00:26:06.020
be less tethered to
other people's agendas

00:26:06.020 --> 00:26:08.365
and to big systems of control.

00:26:11.350 --> 00:26:14.150
And I hope that you
enjoyed this presentation.

00:26:14.150 --> 00:26:16.230
I'm happy to answer
any questions you have.

00:26:16.230 --> 00:26:17.186
So thank you.

