So that's another important
part of the picture.

00:28:07.340 --> 00:28:07.850
Yeah, OK.

00:28:07.850 --> 00:28:08.350
So?

00:28:08.350 --> 00:28:09.542
AUDIENCE: I just had a question.

00:28:09.542 --> 00:28:10.958
How do you make
money while you're

00:28:10.958 --> 00:28:13.885
living in Bolivia [INAUDIBLE]?

00:28:13.885 --> 00:28:15.260
BILL POWERS: How
do I make money?

00:28:15.260 --> 00:28:18.240
Well, so do you
know Juliet Schor

00:28:18.240 --> 00:28:20.280
the economist at Boston College?

00:28:20.280 --> 00:28:23.110
She wrote a lot about this.

00:28:23.110 --> 00:28:25.380
She has a book
called "True Wealth",

00:28:25.380 --> 00:28:28.600
where she talks about
self-provisioning.

00:28:28.600 --> 00:28:32.444
So in the new economy, those
of us sitting in this room

00:28:32.444 --> 00:28:34.360
are lucky enough to have
these types of skills

00:28:34.360 --> 00:28:35.190
that be done anywhere.

00:28:35.190 --> 00:28:37.314
Like that photo I have of
the woman with her laptop

00:28:37.314 --> 00:28:38.724
and her feet in
the water, that's

00:28:38.724 --> 00:28:40.640
what I love about these
wonderful tools is you

00:28:40.640 --> 00:28:42.350
can be anywhere.

00:28:42.350 --> 00:28:46.580
For me personally, I have
multiple income streams from

00:28:46.580 --> 00:28:50.000
different things-- from speaking
engagements, from writing,

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:51.450
from teaching, from--

00:28:51.450 --> 00:28:54.030
AUDIENCE: --travel to the
place where you write, then

00:28:54.030 --> 00:28:56.280
you had to have power
to power your device.

00:28:56.280 --> 00:28:57.613
BILL POWERS: Right, that's true.

00:28:57.613 --> 00:29:02.630
Well so power, we're
actually set up for solar,

00:29:02.630 --> 00:29:04.580
but, as of now,
we're using the town

00:29:04.580 --> 00:29:09.070
power, which is natural gas.

00:29:09.070 --> 00:29:09.570
Yeah.

00:29:09.570 --> 00:29:10.945
So we're not saying
that you have

00:29:10.945 --> 00:29:15.380
to be a radical, off the grid,
self sufficient lifestyle.

00:29:15.380 --> 00:29:17.700
I mean, that's possible,
but I talk about it

00:29:17.700 --> 00:29:19.680
as part of being
self sufficient-ish.

00:29:19.680 --> 00:29:20.380
Right?

00:29:20.380 --> 00:29:21.420
Kind of self sufficient.

00:29:21.420 --> 00:29:23.170
So we're able to produce
a lot of our food

00:29:23.170 --> 00:29:25.670
just right there in front of
that little house that you saw.

00:29:25.670 --> 00:29:28.200
We produce a lot of
our food year round.

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:30.530
And we have 30 kinds
of fruit trees growing

00:29:30.530 --> 00:29:32.550
and everything else.

00:29:32.550 --> 00:29:34.660
We're developing a
little cottage industry

00:29:34.660 --> 00:29:37.035
kind of on the land,
as one income stream.

00:29:37.035 --> 00:29:39.535
There's the writing, my wife
does a little bit of consulting

00:29:39.535 --> 00:29:41.190
at the UN, like
three months a year.

00:29:41.190 --> 00:29:44.410
So you piece that all together
and it adds up to plenty.

00:29:44.410 --> 00:29:49.319
And if you've minimized
your expenses, too you know.

00:29:49.319 --> 00:29:50.360
And that's another thing.

00:29:50.360 --> 00:29:53.310
I recommend Vicki Robin
and Joe Dominguez's book

00:29:53.310 --> 00:29:55.060
"Your Money or Your
Life", which shows you

00:29:55.060 --> 00:29:59.430
how to really look at
what expenses in your life

00:29:59.430 --> 00:30:02.870
don't give you the proper
joy to stuff ratio.

00:30:02.870 --> 00:30:03.540
You know?

00:30:03.540 --> 00:30:04.750
Like how much joy
are you getting out

00:30:04.750 --> 00:30:06.708
of a particular purchase,
that type of an idea.

00:30:06.708 --> 00:30:07.296
We did that.

00:30:07.296 --> 00:30:09.670
We analyzed it very carefully
and we reduced our expenses

00:30:09.670 --> 00:30:10.836
by lot.

00:30:10.836 --> 00:30:12.210
And we also look
at, like OK, how

00:30:12.210 --> 00:30:14.674
do you increase
your hourly income

00:30:14.674 --> 00:30:15.840
in a certain amount of time.

00:30:15.840 --> 00:30:17.660
Even some of the
Tim Ferriss stuff

00:30:17.660 --> 00:30:22.850
about like 80/20 principle,
that you get 20% of your results

00:30:22.850 --> 00:30:24.870
from 80% of your activity.

00:30:24.870 --> 00:30:27.870
So why not do more
in the 20% that

00:30:27.870 --> 00:30:29.919
gives you 80% of the results?

00:30:29.919 --> 00:30:31.210
So working smarter in that way.

00:30:31.210 --> 00:30:32.710
So these are all a
package of things

00:30:32.710 --> 00:30:35.650
that we've applied to
achieve an independence

00:30:35.650 --> 00:30:37.895
from the typical work system.

00:30:37.895 --> 00:30:38.395
Yeah?

00:30:38.395 --> 00:30:39.950
AUDIENCE: Do you have
children to support?

00:30:39.950 --> 00:30:40.866
BILL POWERS: Yes I do.

00:30:40.866 --> 00:30:42.200
I've got two children.

00:30:42.200 --> 00:30:47.170
Two daughters, ages one
and a half, and nine.

00:30:47.170 --> 00:30:50.630
Yeah, I think like, for
example, raising them

00:30:50.630 --> 00:30:53.910
in Bolivia versus New
York City is, for me,

00:30:53.910 --> 00:30:57.350
far better because
you're in a culture that

00:30:57.350 --> 00:31:00.320
is more ecocentric,
more indigenous.

00:31:00.320 --> 00:31:02.050
They're very nature-based.

00:31:02.050 --> 00:31:03.900
And quite frankly,
we're not tied to work,

00:31:03.900 --> 00:31:05.401
so we're with our
kids all the time.

00:31:05.401 --> 00:31:06.983
You know, it's like
we're able to just

00:31:06.983 --> 00:31:08.180
be with them a lot more.

00:31:08.180 --> 00:31:11.500
And they're very in-tuned
to our little creek

00:31:11.500 --> 00:31:18.236
and to the fruit trees, and
they're growing up bilingual.

00:31:18.236 --> 00:31:19.360
There's lots of advantages.

00:31:19.360 --> 00:31:21.120
I'm not saying that everyone
has to move to Bolivia,

00:31:21.120 --> 00:31:22.595
and you're probably
not going to,

00:31:22.595 --> 00:31:25.687
but for us, that
was one edge to push

00:31:25.687 --> 00:31:27.270
that I thought was
really interesting.

00:31:27.270 --> 00:31:28.978
AUDIENCE: I was actually
going to ask you

00:31:28.978 --> 00:31:30.700
what led you to that
town in Bolivia?

00:31:30.700 --> 00:31:33.150
And were there other
places you considered?

00:31:33.150 --> 00:31:35.410
BILL POWERS: Well,
you know, Samaipata,

00:31:35.410 --> 00:31:39.560
which is a Quechua word for
resting in the highlands,

00:31:39.560 --> 00:31:42.819
happened to just really
attract both of us.

00:31:42.819 --> 00:31:45.360
I think that everyone would have
their own place in the world

00:31:45.360 --> 00:31:47.050
that they feel best.

00:31:47.050 --> 00:31:49.750
But for us, I had a
writing fellowship there

00:31:49.750 --> 00:31:52.490
once that they had this
artist's house there that I went

00:31:52.490 --> 00:31:54.660
and, wow!

00:31:54.660 --> 00:31:58.050
Just like, low cost of
living, relatively speaking,

00:31:58.050 --> 00:32:01.240
which is true anywhere
in the developing world.

00:32:01.240 --> 00:32:04.792
And just beautiful national
park and Inca ruins,

00:32:04.792 --> 00:32:06.750
and just this gorgeous
kind of a place to live,

00:32:06.750 --> 00:32:08.090
good climate year round.

00:32:08.090 --> 00:32:11.650
But also just the fact
that you can kind of,

00:32:11.650 --> 00:32:14.250
we call it decolonizing--
sorry that's

00:32:14.250 --> 00:32:15.810
a very academic
term-- decolonizing

00:32:15.810 --> 00:32:19.620
some of our ingrained
habits of over consumption

00:32:19.620 --> 00:32:22.450
and competitiveness
that we found.

00:32:22.450 --> 00:32:24.900
We're both from Ivy League
colleges and all this stuff,

00:32:24.900 --> 00:32:27.100
and from a certain background.

00:32:27.100 --> 00:32:32.550
But we're kinds of decolonizing
a little bit of that ethos.

00:32:32.550 --> 00:32:35.050
And we thought that Samaipata
would be a good place to do it

00:32:35.050 --> 00:32:35.880
and it is.

00:32:35.880 --> 00:32:36.422
It really is.

00:32:36.422 --> 00:32:38.838
AUDIENCE: Are there other
people sharing your [INAUDIBLE]?

00:32:38.838 --> 00:32:39.920
BILL POWERS: Absolutely.

00:32:39.920 --> 00:32:40.450
There are.

00:32:40.450 --> 00:32:41.560
Yeah there are.

00:32:41.560 --> 00:32:42.240
In fact, like I said,
there are people

00:32:42.240 --> 00:32:43.864
from 30 countries
that have come there.

00:32:43.864 --> 00:32:46.600
It's still only 5% of the
village is foreigners, mostly

00:32:46.600 --> 00:32:49.100
Bolivian, which is
nice, nice balance.

00:32:49.100 --> 00:32:51.210
But there's
definitely a community

00:32:51.210 --> 00:32:53.284
of like-- our friends are
ecological architects,

00:32:53.284 --> 00:32:55.200
like the one who designed
our house-- everyone

00:32:55.200 --> 00:32:55.949
lives in the town.

00:32:55.949 --> 00:33:00.630
And 80% of what we consume is
produced there in the town.

00:33:00.630 --> 00:33:05.989
So it's very local and
organic and everything else.

00:33:05.989 --> 00:33:07.280
There are hardships, of course.

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:08.488
Not easy, it's not like here.

00:33:08.488 --> 00:33:10.660
I come back to the
States and you pop up

00:33:10.660 --> 00:33:12.560
on the T in Kendall
Square and it

00:33:12.560 --> 00:33:14.810
has all those beautiful
buildings and stuff like that.

00:33:14.810 --> 00:33:15.750
It's harder.

00:33:15.750 --> 00:33:16.915
It's on the land.

00:33:16.915 --> 00:33:18.540
There's a dirt road
going to our house,

00:33:18.540 --> 00:33:20.248
even though we live
right by the village.

00:33:20.248 --> 00:33:22.340
You're working more,
but like I said,

00:33:22.340 --> 00:33:23.790
humans are a tough species.

00:33:23.790 --> 00:33:25.340
We can adapt to these things.

00:33:25.340 --> 00:33:26.970
Actually, harder is better.

00:33:26.970 --> 00:33:28.950
I can do hard.

00:33:28.950 --> 00:33:29.500
I like that.

00:33:29.500 --> 00:33:31.291
I like having to struggle
a little bit more

00:33:31.291 --> 00:33:33.040
and not having it be too easy.

00:33:33.040 --> 00:33:34.316
That's my perspective.

00:33:34.316 --> 00:33:34.815
Yeah?

00:33:34.815 --> 00:33:37.135
AUDIENCE: So especially
with multiple jobs

00:33:37.135 --> 00:33:38.888
and you say you work harder.

00:33:38.888 --> 00:33:40.760
I'm having a difficult
time balancing that

00:33:40.760 --> 00:33:44.982
with your statement of
working three days, not four.

00:33:44.982 --> 00:33:49.045
What does working
mean and what do you

00:33:49.045 --> 00:33:50.232
do with those other four?

00:33:50.232 --> 00:33:51.690
Are they really
not-- just curious.

00:33:51.690 --> 00:33:53.648
BILL POWERS: So did
everyone hear that question

00:33:53.648 --> 00:33:55.460
about what am I doing
the other four days?

00:33:55.460 --> 00:33:56.220
Oh you didn't hear it?

00:33:56.220 --> 00:33:57.490
He's just saying
how is it possible--

00:33:57.490 --> 00:33:58.770
I'm mentioning all these
different things that I'm

00:33:58.770 --> 00:34:01.353
doing, how is it possible that
there's actually the free time?

00:34:01.353 --> 00:34:01.865
Right?

00:34:01.865 --> 00:34:02.948
AUDIENCE: Well, just yeah.

00:34:02.948 --> 00:34:05.939
What are you defining
the free time as?

00:34:05.939 --> 00:34:07.480
BILL POWERS: That's
a great question.

00:34:07.480 --> 00:34:10.592
But I definitely, when I
was doing the two day work

00:34:10.592 --> 00:34:12.800
week-- which went to a four
day work week in New York

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:16.080
halfway through the book, kind
of had to change, but still

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:20.600
three day weekends-- I clocked
in every five minute interval.

00:34:20.600 --> 00:34:24.270
Whenever I was an a laptop at
all or doing anything related

00:34:24.270 --> 00:34:27.535
to an income stream,
that was work,

00:34:27.535 --> 00:34:29.909
and it counted towards my two,
or three, or four day work

00:34:29.909 --> 00:34:30.580
week.

00:34:30.580 --> 00:34:32.650
OK?

00:34:32.650 --> 00:34:34.870
Now, because we take
these big creativity

00:34:34.870 --> 00:34:37.095
sabbaticals where we're
not doing anything

00:34:37.095 --> 00:34:38.719
and we disconnect
from devices and take

00:34:38.719 --> 00:34:41.889
these internet sabbaticals
and so on, and vacation auto

00:34:41.889 --> 00:34:43.360
response, and we just tune out.

00:34:43.360 --> 00:34:46.250
Like a lot of times we're just
like concentrated on growing

00:34:46.250 --> 00:34:49.330
food, hiking, going back
to beautiful places hiking,

00:34:49.330 --> 00:34:52.550
we love to be outside,
being with family

00:34:52.550 --> 00:34:55.199
in a non-connected
way through work.

00:34:55.199 --> 00:34:56.850
The problem is the
work constantly

00:34:56.850 --> 00:34:57.850
comes through the phone.

00:34:57.850 --> 00:35:01.130
AUDIENCE: So you call growing
food part of the non work?

00:35:01.130 --> 00:35:02.410
BILL POWERS: Yes, definitely.

00:35:02.410 --> 00:35:02.910
Yeah.

00:35:05.510 --> 00:35:09.530
AUDIENCE: That's what I
was going to ask you, too.

00:35:09.530 --> 00:35:13.460
So food production is not
part of your income stream?

00:35:13.460 --> 00:35:17.000
BILL POWERS: Well it is in
the sense that it's, yeah,

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.700
it is self-provisioning.

00:35:19.700 --> 00:35:21.420
But it just doesn't
feel like work

00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:23.594
at the level we're doing it.

00:35:23.594 --> 00:35:25.135
It's not like we
have this huge farm.

00:35:25.135 --> 00:35:28.630
We're producing it just
intensively around the house

00:35:28.630 --> 00:35:30.180
and fruit tree
production, and so on,

00:35:30.180 --> 00:35:32.260
like maybe 10 hours
a week or less

00:35:32.260 --> 00:35:33.760
that we're actually
putting into it.

00:35:33.760 --> 00:35:36.050
We're not turning
into this big thing.

00:35:36.050 --> 00:35:38.550
I guess what I didn't say is a
lot of really what this comes

00:35:38.550 --> 00:35:40.966
down to-- and I don't know if
this appeals to you or not--

00:35:40.966 --> 00:35:44.460
but for me and for my wife and
our kids, what appeals to us

00:35:44.460 --> 00:35:45.819
is doing nothing, too.

00:35:45.819 --> 00:35:47.360
I mean, oh god, it
sounds so radical.

00:35:47.360 --> 00:35:50.760
But taking four or five hours
a day and just doing nothing,

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:56.570
like just walking behind our
house, or just meditation.

00:35:56.570 --> 00:35:59.857
Or literally, and
this sounds crazy,

00:35:59.857 --> 00:36:02.440
like walking to your neighbors
and just hanging out with them.

00:36:02.440 --> 00:36:05.060
Like people do that
in this village.

00:36:05.060 --> 00:36:08.340
You just stop by and
have tea with someone.

00:36:08.340 --> 00:36:10.580
Or you just sit in your
hammock for a couple hours,

00:36:10.580 --> 00:36:11.666
like all of these things.

00:36:11.666 --> 00:36:13.040
It's like the way
we used to live

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:15.730
when I was a kid in the
'70s, or something like that.

00:36:15.730 --> 00:36:19.121
Before we got into this
culture of a lot of speed,

00:36:19.121 --> 00:36:21.246
it's that more relaxed
summer vacation type of feel

00:36:21.246 --> 00:36:22.660
that we bring to
our whole lives.

00:36:22.660 --> 00:36:23.534
Does that make sense?

00:36:26.430 --> 00:36:28.390
So we consciously
integrate all of that

00:36:28.390 --> 00:36:31.227
into our lives, that free
time and that nothing time.

00:36:31.227 --> 00:36:32.560
It comes actually out of Africa.

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:35.870
I lived in Africa for a couple
years, and what I realized

00:36:35.870 --> 00:36:38.120
was that people had to spend
four or five hours a day

00:36:38.120 --> 00:36:40.500
doing nothing, playing soccer,
sitting in the hammocks,

00:36:40.500 --> 00:36:41.860
or they weren't happy.

00:36:41.860 --> 00:36:44.090
They have this leisure ethic
instead of a work ethic.

00:36:44.090 --> 00:36:45.465
And that's kind
of what taught me

00:36:45.465 --> 00:36:47.924
about this idea of not
always being-- yeah?

00:36:47.924 --> 00:36:50.460
AUDIENCE: Why no wood
stove in the cabin?

00:36:50.460 --> 00:36:52.750
BILL POWERS: Why no wood
stove in the 12 by 12?

00:36:52.750 --> 00:36:54.860
There is a space
for a wood stove,

00:36:54.860 --> 00:36:57.670
and the physician that
lives there to this day

00:36:57.670 --> 00:37:01.290
could've put one
in, but she did not.

00:37:01.290 --> 00:37:03.440
She decided that she
was just perfectly happy

00:37:03.440 --> 00:37:06.610
being cold when it got cold
and putting on extra layers

00:37:06.610 --> 00:37:08.434
and making more tea.

00:37:08.434 --> 00:37:10.210
AUDIENCE: Cold when
it's 10 below outside?

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:12.209
BILL POWERS: Well, I mean,
it is North Carolina.

00:37:12.209 --> 00:37:15.580
So it's not Boston.

00:37:15.580 --> 00:37:19.280
So it gets down to 20,
sometimes, at the coldest.

00:37:19.280 --> 00:37:24.966
But it's usually like 30s
or 40s at the very coldest.

00:37:24.966 --> 00:37:26.900
AUDIENCE: Is there a washroom?

00:37:26.900 --> 00:37:28.360
BILL POWERS: In the 12 by 12?

00:37:28.360 --> 00:37:28.925
OK.

00:37:28.925 --> 00:37:31.760
The 12 by 12 has two porches
in the front the back.

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:34.040
And the back porch has
a composting toilet.

00:37:34.040 --> 00:37:35.320
There's this-- have you
heard of, you probably

00:37:35.320 --> 00:37:37.403
haven't-- but it's called
the "Humanure Handbook."

00:37:37.403 --> 00:37:41.176
It's a contraction of human
manure, "Humanure Handbook."

00:37:41.176 --> 00:37:43.550
Teaches you all the different
types of composting toilets

00:37:43.550 --> 00:37:44.040
you can make.

00:37:44.040 --> 00:37:46.081
That was right there on
the shelf when I arrived.

00:37:46.081 --> 00:37:48.430
And I had to figure
how to use this thing.

00:37:48.430 --> 00:37:50.221
But basically, you go
out on the back porch

00:37:50.221 --> 00:37:52.830
and it's like a five
gallon bucket, hidden,

00:37:52.830 --> 00:37:54.410
and then there's a toilet seat.

00:37:54.410 --> 00:37:56.320
And there are cedar
chips beside it.

00:37:56.320 --> 00:37:59.100
And when it fills up, you
just dump it in a compost pile

00:37:59.100 --> 00:38:00.950
and it becomes compost.

00:38:00.950 --> 00:38:01.830
That's it.

00:38:01.830 --> 00:38:02.640
It's very simple.

00:38:02.640 --> 00:38:05.550
It doesn't smell at all.

00:38:05.550 --> 00:38:08.107
And then the water for
washing was a solar shower

00:38:08.107 --> 00:38:09.440
that I'd put out in the morning.

00:38:09.440 --> 00:38:10.481
The sun would heat it up.

00:38:10.481 --> 00:38:12.785
You hang it from a
tree and you shower.

00:38:12.785 --> 00:38:14.910
And then, the water for
washing up dishes and stuff

00:38:14.910 --> 00:38:16.034
was also on the back porch.

00:38:16.034 --> 00:38:18.780
And that's just from rainwater
catchment from the house.

00:38:18.780 --> 00:38:21.380
So she's got this whole system
that she applies and lives off

00:38:21.380 --> 00:38:21.880
of.

00:38:21.880 --> 00:38:23.229
It liberates her time.

00:38:23.229 --> 00:38:24.770
She donates her time
as a doctor now.

00:38:24.770 --> 00:38:27.302
She doesn't even have to
really work for money.

00:38:27.302 --> 00:38:28.264
Yeah?

00:38:28.264 --> 00:38:30.669
AUDIENCE: I don't know if
this is a legitimate question.

00:38:30.669 --> 00:38:34.517
Help me form it into a question.

00:38:34.517 --> 00:38:36.441
How much land do you
need of agriculture

00:38:36.441 --> 00:38:37.890
for a person to live off of?

00:38:37.890 --> 00:38:39.502
BILL POWERS: That's
a great question.

00:38:39.502 --> 00:38:40.960
Jonathan, is it
possible to pass me

00:38:40.960 --> 00:38:42.670
that-- I guess I
could just grab it.

00:38:42.670 --> 00:38:44.690
If you'll just pass me
that bottle of water?

00:38:44.690 --> 00:38:47.160
Four and 1/2 acres is
what-- OK, the question

00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:49.990
is how much land you need
to live off of, right?

00:38:49.990 --> 00:38:52.310
Thanks a lot.

00:38:52.310 --> 00:38:55.550
Agronomists have said that with
four and a half acres, which

00:38:55.550 --> 00:38:59.570
is a little bit-- we
have five, five and 1/2--

00:38:59.570 --> 00:39:01.070
every person on the
planet, even all

00:39:01.070 --> 00:39:04.140
seven billion people
organized in families--

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:08.160
could have 4 and 1/2 acres each
and live very sustainably off

00:39:08.160 --> 00:39:09.236
of that.

00:39:09.236 --> 00:39:10.860
And there would be
lots of wild forests

00:39:10.860 --> 00:39:11.901
and lots of conservation.

00:39:11.901 --> 00:39:15.432
Doesn't sound
realistic, but it is.

00:39:15.432 --> 00:39:17.140
There's a lot of
acreage we're using just

00:39:17.140 --> 00:39:19.184
in ridiculously
ineffective ways.

00:39:19.184 --> 00:39:21.100
AUDIENCE: So 4 and 1/2
per person, per family?

00:39:21.100 --> 00:39:22.035
BILL POWERS: Per family.

00:39:22.035 --> 00:39:22.534
Yeah.

00:39:25.600 --> 00:39:27.316
We could easily
live off our land.

00:39:27.316 --> 00:39:29.635
I mean, the soil
is so productive--

00:39:29.635 --> 00:39:31.317
AUDIENCE: Not living
in Somerville.

00:39:31.317 --> 00:39:32.900
BILL POWERS: Not
living in Somerville.

00:39:32.900 --> 00:39:33.400
Yeah.

00:39:33.400 --> 00:39:37.490
I'm just saying you could, think
about it, anyone in this room,

00:39:37.490 --> 00:39:39.540
either this year or
within five years easily,

00:39:39.540 --> 00:39:41.530
could do what we did
if you wanted to.

00:39:41.530 --> 00:39:43.200
You could liquidate
what you have here

00:39:43.200 --> 00:39:46.550
and get something so
beautiful somewhere else where

00:39:46.550 --> 00:39:50.170
the cost of living is
lower and you could do it.

00:39:50.170 --> 00:39:52.310
I'm not saying you're gonna.

00:39:52.310 --> 00:39:56.500
But you have that power
and the resources.

00:39:56.500 --> 00:39:57.000
Yeah?

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:00.297
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
you were [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:00.297 --> 00:40:03.520
Is that the case?

00:40:03.520 --> 00:40:06.360
BILL POWERS: I still am on
the adjunct faculty at NYU

00:40:06.360 --> 00:40:09.920
and I bring students to Bolivia
and I teach the sustainable

00:40:09.920 --> 00:40:12.170
development global
field intensive,

00:40:12.170 --> 00:40:14.432
where we look at models of
how to develop sustainably.

00:40:14.432 --> 00:40:15.890
Like with these
graduates students.

00:40:15.890 --> 00:40:19.660
So I'm not on a sabbatical.

00:40:19.660 --> 00:40:21.660
I meant like I'm on a
creativity sabbatical that

00:40:21.660 --> 00:40:23.802
means-- we come up
with our own lexicon.

00:40:23.802 --> 00:40:26.260
I don't know if you ever read
"Mountains Beyond Mountains",

00:40:26.260 --> 00:40:30.130
Paul Farmer, the
physician at Harvard.

00:40:30.130 --> 00:40:33.200
They created the whole lexicon
around poverty, reduction,

00:40:33.200 --> 00:40:33.700
and so on.

00:40:33.700 --> 00:40:35.616
We have a whole lexicon
around all this stuff.

00:40:35.616 --> 00:40:38.270
So creativity
sabbaticals just means

00:40:38.270 --> 00:40:41.120
I'm not going to work
for, like, two months,

00:40:41.120 --> 00:40:44.080
and we're going to
just develop new ideas.

00:40:44.080 --> 00:40:44.940
Whatever we want.

00:40:44.940 --> 00:40:47.065
Like in other words, we're
not tied to anyone else.

00:40:47.065 --> 00:40:49.450
So we're going to come up
with new-- that's what it is.

00:40:49.450 --> 00:40:52.022
So writing a new book.

00:40:52.022 --> 00:40:53.480
Whatever creative
project, starting

00:40:53.480 --> 00:40:54.570
some kind of cottage industry.

00:40:54.570 --> 00:40:56.611
Whatever it is, that's
our creativity sabbatical.

00:40:56.611 --> 00:40:59.687
AUDIENCE: I was asking do
you have an end date to leave

00:40:59.687 --> 00:41:01.584
your life over
there and come back?

00:41:01.584 --> 00:41:03.000
BILL POWERS: Do I
have an end date

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:05.880
to leave my life over
there and come back?

00:41:05.880 --> 00:41:07.750
No.

00:41:07.750 --> 00:41:08.580
Not really.

00:41:08.580 --> 00:41:10.410
I mean, we do have
our place in New York.

00:41:10.410 --> 00:41:12.140
We just rent it out.

00:41:12.140 --> 00:41:15.510
Another income stream.

00:41:15.510 --> 00:41:16.940
But--

00:41:16.940 --> 00:41:19.440
AUDIENCE: I was asking because
your approach to your life

00:41:19.440 --> 00:41:22.420
could have been different if
you had a time limit applied.

00:41:22.420 --> 00:41:22.920
OK.

00:41:22.920 --> 00:41:25.395
I will live there like
two years and then

00:41:25.395 --> 00:41:26.880
I will go back to my other life.

00:41:30.810 --> 00:41:32.600
BILL POWERS: As far
as we're concerned,

00:41:32.600 --> 00:41:37.240
I've never been happier
than I am now in this town,

00:41:37.240 --> 00:41:40.480
living at this smallest
beautiful scale with community.

00:41:40.480 --> 00:41:41.700
Everyone knows me.

00:41:41.700 --> 00:41:43.160
We have beautiful nature.

00:41:43.160 --> 00:41:45.620
It's like, what
more could we want?

00:41:45.620 --> 00:41:48.420
In terms of having the absolute
best schools and so on,

00:41:48.420 --> 00:41:52.150
I mean, again that's
another idea in our heads

00:41:52.150 --> 00:41:54.460
that you have to have
the perfect everything

00:41:54.460 --> 00:41:55.540
for your kids.

00:41:55.540 --> 00:41:56.710
So I'm notching that down.

00:41:56.710 --> 00:41:59.110
I'm realizing that
Amaya and Clea may not

00:41:59.110 --> 00:42:02.140
have the absolute
best of everything.

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:04.745
We're going to give them a
wonderful life and education

00:42:04.745 --> 00:42:06.900
and basis and they
can go from there.

00:42:06.900 --> 00:42:12.500
But maybe it won't be even
the level my wife and I had.

00:42:12.500 --> 00:42:17.240
But it's like, I do think that
this kind of disease-- you

00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:21.896
might even call it a disease--
around kind of over educating

00:42:21.896 --> 00:42:23.270
our kids or
overstimulating them.

00:42:23.270 --> 00:42:25.320
Like this sort of
helicopter parenting

00:42:25.320 --> 00:42:28.867
and over scheduling kids is not
going in the right direction,

00:42:28.867 --> 00:42:29.450
in my opinion.

00:42:32.530 --> 00:42:33.030
Yeah?

00:42:33.030 --> 00:42:35.404
AUDIENCE: What are some of
the most surprising things you

00:42:35.404 --> 00:42:38.321
learned about yourself in this
transition to live slowly?

00:42:38.321 --> 00:42:40.320
BILL POWERS: What are the
most surprising things

00:42:40.320 --> 00:42:42.445
I learned about myself in
this transition to living

00:42:42.445 --> 00:42:43.650
more slowly?

00:42:43.650 --> 00:42:48.420
That you can find a lot
more happiness and joy

00:42:48.420 --> 00:42:50.470
in unexpected ways.

00:42:50.470 --> 00:42:55.480
That when you tie your
self esteem and everything

00:42:55.480 --> 00:43:00.420
to your position in life
and your amount of income

00:43:00.420 --> 00:43:02.780
and your status, you're
bound to always be unhappy

00:43:02.780 --> 00:43:04.960
because there's
always someone higher.

00:43:04.960 --> 00:43:06.730
As soon as you get
rid of that idea,

00:43:06.730 --> 00:43:09.980
and you step out of this culture
and into a culture like Bolivia

00:43:09.980 --> 00:43:13.712
where nobody has those ideas,
or it's a very low idea.

00:43:13.712 --> 00:43:15.420
Much higher is how
interconnected are you

00:43:15.420 --> 00:43:17.400
with others.

00:43:17.400 --> 00:43:20.680
It's like people are people
through other people.

00:43:20.680 --> 00:43:23.220
It surprised me that,
oh, I get self esteem

00:43:23.220 --> 00:43:25.540
from just being
helpful to people

00:43:25.540 --> 00:43:28.120
and being part of this group.

00:43:28.120 --> 00:43:29.580
So that's one of the things.

00:43:29.580 --> 00:43:30.528
Yeah?

00:43:30.528 --> 00:43:31.950
AUDIENCE: Just one thought.

00:43:31.950 --> 00:43:35.742
A couple family friends
who sort of downsized,

00:43:35.742 --> 00:43:39.450
one challenge, especially in the
US, is their medical expenses.

00:43:39.450 --> 00:43:41.940
Say you reduce
your income and you

00:43:41.940 --> 00:43:44.332
live-- I have a friend who's
a captain on a boat, lives

00:43:44.332 --> 00:43:45.075
on a boat.

00:43:45.075 --> 00:43:45.926
Very low income.

00:43:45.926 --> 00:43:47.550
Another one a
perpetually touring band,

00:43:47.550 --> 00:43:49.530
another one in a small cabin.

00:43:49.530 --> 00:43:50.520
You know?

00:43:50.520 --> 00:43:52.995
And it's great, but
the US is particularly

00:43:52.995 --> 00:43:56.960
challenged because the
medical system we have.

00:43:56.960 --> 00:43:59.425
You see anything in
different cultures that

00:43:59.425 --> 00:44:02.140
or are economists
thinking about that?

00:44:02.140 --> 00:44:04.640
BILL POWERS: I'm amazed at how
a country like Bolivia, which

00:44:04.640 --> 00:44:08.180
is the second poorest,
economically, in Latin America

00:44:08.180 --> 00:44:11.560
has almost a better
medical system than we do.

00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:13.875
For our baby daughter,
a doctor would

00:44:13.875 --> 00:44:16.810
come like every two months to
our house and check up on her

00:44:16.810 --> 00:44:17.990
and then give her the
shots there with the nurse.

00:44:17.990 --> 00:44:18.770
This whole team would come.

00:44:18.770 --> 00:44:20.980
They'd go around to
everyone's house and do it.

00:44:20.980 --> 00:44:22.669
How are they able to do that?

00:44:22.669 --> 00:44:23.710
My mom was down visiting.

00:44:23.710 --> 00:44:24.543
She had an accident.

00:44:24.543 --> 00:44:26.364
We went to the hospital
in Samaipata there.

00:44:26.364 --> 00:44:27.780
They treated her
right away and it

00:44:27.780 --> 00:44:29.300
was 30 Bolivianos was the bill.

00:44:29.300 --> 00:44:30.760
Four dollars.

00:44:30.760 --> 00:44:32.434
I don't understand.

00:44:32.434 --> 00:44:33.600
It's a socialist government.

00:44:33.600 --> 00:44:35.110
The government is socialist.

00:44:35.110 --> 00:44:38.670
And they have these policies
they're redistributing.

00:44:38.670 --> 00:44:40.780
They tax the companys
at high levels,

00:44:40.780 --> 00:44:43.030
like the oil and gas companies,
the mining companies,

00:44:43.030 --> 00:44:45.330
and they just redistribute
to health and education.

00:44:45.330 --> 00:44:46.430
So that's part of it.

00:44:46.430 --> 00:44:48.830
And so it's
universal, basically.

00:44:48.830 --> 00:44:53.080
The care, obviously, is not
the Harvard Medical School

00:44:53.080 --> 00:44:54.370
facility, obviously.

00:44:54.370 --> 00:44:56.520
Again, we've seen
it as accepting

00:44:56.520 --> 00:44:59.400
a slightly lower level of care.

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:01.490
You know, we can go to
Santa Cruz two hours away

00:45:01.490 --> 00:45:02.950
if we really needed
something that

00:45:02.950 --> 00:45:07.250
was US level or close to it.

00:45:07.250 --> 00:45:09.410
But on a daily
basis, we're not tied

00:45:09.410 --> 00:45:13.110
into super high powered medical.

00:45:13.110 --> 00:45:15.400
We do have insurance.

00:45:15.400 --> 00:45:17.490
Someone like us
living-- you can have

00:45:17.490 --> 00:45:20.960
an evacuation plan, very cheap.

00:45:20.960 --> 00:45:24.780
And you can have
catastrophic, like where

00:45:24.780 --> 00:45:26.607
you pay a deductible,
and then for a couple

00:45:26.607 --> 00:45:28.190
hundred dollars a
month or, something,

00:45:28.190 --> 00:45:29.481
you're covered for your family.

00:45:29.481 --> 00:45:31.574
So it's totally doable.

00:45:31.574 --> 00:45:34.014
AUDIENCE: How much of this
is made possible by the fact

00:45:34.014 --> 00:45:36.454
that on a global
scale you're wealthy.

00:45:36.454 --> 00:45:37.918
You were born in the US.

00:45:37.918 --> 00:45:39.870
So therefore, on a
global scale, you

